text.text:
No matter how cool and aloof your beb might seem, we’re yet to encounter a person on the planet able to withstand the mythical power of a snuggle. Want to have a first date to remember? Go for a snuggle. Want to take things to the next level? Snuggle. Need to relight the fire? Try polyamory - if that fails, do some snuggling. Here are the snuggest little snuggle spots in town for some grade-A snuggling. 

NB. We are trying to enter the Guinness Book of Records for the highest use of the word 'snuggle' in a feature.

tip.text: Sure, the prices are kind of steep but this isn't the place for your weekly flick: this is the place for those push-the-boat-all-the-way-out-so-you-can't-even-see-land-anymore-type occasions. When you're seeking to woo someone/leave the dog house. There are 65 leather armchairs with footstools and side tables, 3 two-seater sofas and cashmere blankets; there are even six double beds at the front. This is something swish, something swanky and sometimes, you need a bit of that with your movie.

text.text: Probably the OG of snug spots, Electric Cinema currently has a 98% success rate for dates at the time of writing. Catch a (slightly expensive) flick here on their two-seater sofas or six double beds that come with cashmere blankets - you'll be so cosy you'll probably end up hiding beneath the blankets when the film ends, forcing security to physically separate and then remove you.

tip.text:
Whenever we’re lacking an animate object to give us a hug, we drop in on Canonbury’s diminutive Myddleton Arms: the poster boy for the cosy, atmospheric British boozer. The beer selection is decent, whilst the food selection is limited (strictly burgers from a BBQ outside), but that’s not what this pub is about - it’s that intangible feeling of snugness; a setting made for long Sundays spent in a comfortable, escapist warm daze.

It truly comes into its own in winter: that’s when you can hunker down before the open fire, play some of the board games they’ve got, or head out back to their snug cabins, built with their own speaker systems and ideal for a group meet. Actually, it's ideal for something slightly more intimate than a meet to be frank, but this is a PG publication. When hibernation beckons, this is the one.

text.text: The Myddleton Arms is just made for hibernating. It really comes into its own in winter, when you can hunker down before the open fire, play some of the board games they’ve got, or head out back to their cosy cabins, built with their own speaker systems and ideal for a stolen smooch. Actually, it's ideal for something slightly more intimate than a smooch, but this is a PG publication.

tip.text:
Think you've seen it all, and drunk in it all? Wilton's Music Hall is the oldest Victorian music hall to survive anywhere in the world. It's grand, shabby-chic, and pretty damn beautiful. Not only can you come see a show here, but also have a cocktail mixed up in style too.

The Mahogany Bar here actually dates back to 1690 and feels its age, but in a good way. The cocktails stick to the classic recipes, and you can get takeaway ordered in to your table. Everyone should come here at least once.

text.text: It might not exactly be a secret, but Wilton's Music Hall is still a strangely lowkey gem - which is just great for the purposes of a snuggle. It's the world's oldest Victorian music hall and the bar, dating back to 1690, is a really beautiful space, perfecting that shabby-chic, rustic aesthetic. With many a secluded nook and cranny here, the conditions are fertile for intimacy.

tip.text:
This is what Arabian nights are made of: part souk, part bohemian lounge, Cafe Cairo makes the perfect sanctuary from the high street drivel. A cosy den of dim lighting, snug seating and wayward musicians, this spot has all sorts rubbing their eyes in disbelief, but it's not a mirage - it's real, and we're into it. Aladdin, eat your damn heart out.

The movement (yeah, it's a movement) started 20 years ago when Cafe Cairo was merely a tent at Glastonbury. It developed a bit of a cult following, and soon found a permanent home in Brixton. Some of the old regulars still come round, alongside shiny new patrons smoking shisha side by side. What else? Banging pizzas, cabaret nights, live music, free film screenings on Sundays, and unlimited free toast, that's what else. This is one of the last true beacons of community in London - get here quick.

text.text: Here we have the snuggle but with a refreshing exotic twist. Brixton's Cafe Cairo is part souk, part bohemian lounge: a cosy den of dim lighting, snug seating and wayward musicians. Expect banging pizzas, cabaret nights, live music and plenty of soft furnishings for some comfy time.

tip.text: If it’s an elaborate drink you’re after, craft beer haunt The Rose and Crown will most definitely have you covered. Boasting an inspiringly eclectic lineup of rotating bevvies and ever honing the spotlight on small, local and quite often crazy breweries – you can expect to wrap your gob around everything from shortbread-flavoured beer to tropical punch-flavoured beer and everything in between. Also on the cards is an incredibly unique and innovative snack menu, live music, comedy nights and a spectacularly dingy, club-like basement that’s available for hire.

text.text: The Rose & Crown is a super atmospheric haunt; a staple choice when we require a place with good drinks (they've plenty of craft beers); good food (excellent kitchen residencies); and entertainment in case the date is lacking (live music and comedy on the regs). It's a one-room deal with all the candles, soft furnishings, and convivial vibes that make a snuggle almost an inevitability.

tip.text:
Damn this is a pretty pub. It's as old as the hills (meaning the 1820s), and they've happily made a real effort to maintain those dope Victorian stylings. That means super low doorways, beautiful dark wood everywhere and cosy little cubbyholes featuring a sherry bar, a roaring fire and jovial west Londoners sipping on ales.

The classics are all on show in the kitchen (fish and chips, steak sandwiches etc) but at slightly gastro-inflated prices, naturally. But Venison steak with orange marmalade jus, braised red cabbage & heritage potatoes is gonna cost you pal, especially when the quality is excellent and portion sizes generous. When you throw in a heated beer garden, it's no surprise that this is a popular little spot. Reserving is a necessity.

text.text: Damn this is a pretty pub. As old as the hills (meaning the 1820s), they've happily made a real effort to maintain those dope Victorian stylings with low doorways, beautiful dark wood everywhere and cosy little cubbyholes featuring a sherry bar and a roaring fire. A perfect place to end up in after a winter's walk when you can, you guessed it, get into some snuggling.

tip.text: Opposite Islington Green and built in 1913, this place is one of the longest running cinemas in the UK. It's ornate facade is pretty eye catching with red and green neon and a huge board outside advertising what's going on, like they did it back in the good old days. Inside expect plush armchairs, popcorn and big-screen favourites from the past and present on their single screen.

text.text: Another cinema, and this time a cutesy single screen that harks back to 1913 - a time when snuggles were practically illegal. Oh how far we've come. The place you really wanna find yourself here is on the mezzanine level by the bar. Here you'll find two person sofas, footstalls, and easy access to booze. Tickets are a little more spenny but you cannot put a price on a snuggle - and don't trust people who tell you you can.

tip.text: Just a standard pub by the station? Wrong. This pub might have one too many shabby chic lampshades downstairs but head up to the first floor and have a good long sit in the swanky library bar. Bored of books? Don’t worry there’s a secret cinema room in the basement. (They post which films are playing every week and are always up for suggestions.) The food here puts pub grub to shame with quite an ambitious menu and a tasty selection of finger food. We love their scotch eggs, their piggies in blankets and their boxed baked camembert - we could go on.

text.text: What at first appears to be a regular neighbourhood boozer is way more than that. On the first floor is the swanky library bar with plenty of red on the walls, on the sofas and in the wine glasses resulting in a warming, languid atmosphere. There's even a secret cinema room in the basement if you want to take that snuggling to the next level or watch a film to avoid conversation.

tip.text:
Those lamenting the death of community spirit should get themselves to The Ivy House sharpish. The place is absolutely rife with the sweet stuff, from live music events and knitting classes, to the fact that back in 2012 - when faced with imminent closure - it became the first building in the UK to be bought for the community under the provisions of the Localism Act. It's now owned by an impressive 350 community shareholders.

Even if that knowledge doesn't make you feel all warm and fuzzy inside, the wood panelling, proper old-school stage, wooden booths, fairy lights, books and board games should do something for ya. And then there's the feeling you get when you walk in: that you're truly welcome and the unmistakable sense that we're all in this thing together. It'll be enough to prompt you to break into song at any moment. There are charming pubs, really charming pubs and then there's The Ivy House.

text.text: Here's a setting where the community spirit is almost palpable. Owned by 350 community shareholders, The Ivy House is a verified institution with wood panelling, a proper old-school stage, wooden booths, fairy lights, an open fire, books and board games. It'll have you and boo feeling all warm and fuzzy inside which normally leads to... you know what.

tip.text:
Rather a different vibe to your average date night - this hidden speakeasy located above the Exmouth arms offers a very personal feel, with only 30 seats and no standing allowed. So once you're in, you're one of the lucky few who'll get to taste the ever changing cocktail menu.

Sit in amongst dark interiors, leather upholstered chairs, kooky art and neon signage, while you choose from the revival section of their menu for twists on the classics. We liked the 'Very Junipery Fig Sour' with overproof gin, artisanal fig jam, lemon juice, sugar and egg white; or if your date has a bit of a sweet tooth surprise them with a Peter Pan's Forbidden Milkshake, made from bourbon, creme de banane, ginger liqueur, natural vanilla, cream and egg. Then watch them lick their lips and gaze adoringly at you. Job done.

text.text: Whilst Exmouth Arms often gets rammo (and is NOT a good shout for a date), upstairs is a fairly unknown secret: a hidden speakeasy with dark interiors, leather upholstered chairs, only 30 seats and loose no-standing policy. Get a table here and you're pretty much set. The cocktails are also above the standard fare and sometimes come with table service - which is handy because it means snuggles can proceed uninterrupted.
